            Hi, Kelly. 



First, in exhaustive search you would be trying every possible 

genetic combination. This is extremely vast space. NEAT searches 

through the genotype space of the well known NNs even in novelty 

search and indirect encodings like HyperNEAT. The difference is how 

fitness scores are assigned and what is being evaluated. The 

phenotypes are evaluated, not the genotypes. It is important no note 

that you can have any number of genomes collapsing to the same 

phenotypic behavior. But in NS you are looking for new behaviors, not 

new genomes. 

I agree that this map can be solved by just sticking to a wall but 

what is more important is that if you try fitness search on the same 

map, you will be unable to solve it no matter how long you wait. I 

wrote this simple demo just to see this idea in action. Of course 

there is no practical application :) 

As I mentioned before some time, sticking to the maze domain may not 

be the best way to study this new algorithm. But it is good for 

demonstration purposes. 



Peter



